values.comments:
Ethics introduces some of the central issues and texts in the philosophical study of morality in the Western tradition. Issues examined include: the nature of morality (what makes a person good or bad?), the relation between morality and religion (if there is no God is everything permitted?), the nature of the good life and the place of morality within it (why should I be moral?), as well as selected practical moral issues such as abortion, affirmative action, and responses to world hunger. Readings are drawn both from historical sources (Plato, Aristotle, Cicero, Epictetus, Hobbes, Hume, Kant, and Mill) and from contemporary authors such as Peter Singer, Judity Thompson, and Bernard Williams. &#8232;&#8232;

Students observed that Ethics was “one of the most thought-provoking and invaluable courses” they’d taken at Penn, finding “the material and course overall wonderful,” “organized pretty well,” and “truly interesting and inspiring.” Overall, students felt this is a “really interesting course that makes you see things in a different light.” &#8232;&#8232;

Professor Meyer is “enthusiastic and knowledgeable, and always well prepared.” She typically “did a great job with her lectures” and “everything was very understandable…due mostly to her organization.” One student felt that Professor Meyer “overcomplicates” her “simple topics.” Additionally, another student mentioned that her “powerpoints could be made a little easier to read,” but students all agreed her pace was satisfactory for an introductory level class. &#8232;

This is an introductory course for PPE majors. As such, “readings were quite manageable,” “grading is fair,” and TAs were generally noted as helpful. Students recommended this class to any potential PPE major, citing it as “a good intro level course.” Students were universally frustrated with the clicker, which functioned as both a grade and a measure of attendance. Students felt “your grade should be based on how well you understand the material (which can be evaluated via papers, exams, etc); your grade should not be based on how often you come to class.”
